      "message": "I think we should get away from the habit of hardcoding operational details on *concrete* Chops deployment in *supposedly reusable* LUCI source code. GAE promoted this ugly practice by blurring the line between builds and deploys. We should not repeat this mistake with k8s. \n\nWith k8s there are multiple distinct stage:\n1. Build process. It takes sources as input and spits out some local Docker image as output.\n2. Publishing the image. It takes a docker image and uploads it to some registry.\n3. Rolling out the image. It takes published image and deploys into one or many Kubernetes clusters.\n\nStage 1 is pure local transformation from source code to an image. There\u0027s no hardcoded operational details here yet. It is OK (even good) when Dockerfile lives side by side with source code it \"wraps\".\n\nStage 2 has some operation configuration (a docker registry to push the image to). It can potentially live in the same source code tree, but doesn\u0027t have to.\n\nStage 3 has A LOT of operational details (names of our clusters, their location, sizes, etc. etc.). This information is specific to us and must not be committed into luci-go repository. At most we can commit some common template for k8s configs, and then apply all our specifics in some other repo, which will closely \"track\" what *we* deploy.\n\nIs it imperative for Kubernetes configs to live in this repository? We can start as is, but prepare for them to be moved or significantly refactored in the future.",
      "revId": "4cde97ef079718d2ec7e1e4354cd5d55928112bb",
